Excerpts from
http://www.businessweek.com/investor/content/jul2007/pi20070713_19008...

RadioShack's ongoing cuts to its workforce and advertising costs will
lead to disappointing comparable-store sales and lower profits for the
foreseeable future. Reduced commissions and benefit packages are also
hurting employee morale.

Even before being shut out of the iPhone market, RadioShack had been
losing significant market share in wireless products to carriers and
big-box stores.

RadioShack needed to slash costs just to keep pace with falling sales,
but most of the cost reductions to date have centered on
brand-building efforts that might have expanded the customer base. Any
new cuts from now will probably eat into advertising that drives store
traffic and promotional events, and that's sure to hurt sales going
forward.

What RadioShack appears to be missing is any sense of a longer-term
strategy toward bringing in new merchandise and finding ways to
generate higher margins.

Having gone through numerous boom-bust cycles, the retailer is sorely
in need of a new hot product now that wireless and satellite radio on
on the decline. The GPS navigation device has done very well, but the
market isn't large enough to offset slowing sales in other categories.

--

