Shrug. Economic Darwinism in action. RS wrote off their original core
market, the electronic hobbyist, years ago. They tried to go mainstream,
with mall locations, too many locations, Â and major-media advertising, vs.
the 2nd-tier strip centers and mailed flyers and catalogs that built the
company. Doubt I go in the local RS more than once or twice a year anymore-
they simply no longer carry much that I need, or can't find cheaper
elsewhere. Lousy selection, high prices, untrained staff-&gt; lower sales -&gt;
the downward spiral begins. I do feel sorry for the career employees, and
the kids that had an interest in electronics that no longer have entry-level
jobs to start their careers. And it is a pain to have to buy parts online,
or take off work to go to an actual industrial supply. But RS as a
corporation did it to themselves- they are now little more than a cell phone
and techno-toy store, and others (real world and online) do that better and
cheaper. I give them another few years before they go online-only, or go
belly-up entirely. IIRC, a major part of their business is now the
non-RS-labeled cell phone kiosk stands they run in malls and other stores
like Sam' Club.

'Radio Shack- You've got Questions- We've got Blank Stares'

